This adds hardcoded emoji for the suggested statuses.

', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 12, 21, 21, 5, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 546929248, 'comment_body': "I can test-deploy this on chat.zulip.org for folks to play with it if so -- but we'll of course want to build a full feature.  Have you QAed it enough that you'd encourage test-deploying?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 12, 21, 21, 5, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 547111257, 'comment_body': "yes, the hard coding was to avoid database changes and I'd encourage test deploying.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 12, 22, 7, 24, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'YashRE42', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 675835779, 'comment_body': "This function basically duplicates a function from `reactions.js`; I think we should try to move that parsing logic to a new `emoji.get_emoji_by_name` that can be called from both code paths and returns an object with all these properties.  

Can you do that rework?  It doesn't look like this is every called with any other parameters, so that seems cleaner.  ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 23, 19, 59, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 676606525, 'comment_body': 'Added the new commit refactoring this, though instead of naming the function `get_emoji_by_name` I named it `get_emoji_details_by_name` as there already exists a function with the name `get_emoji_name`,

https://github.com/zulip/zulip/blob/779a2f33171a345d18971dccc61fc31ae395ba3a/static/shared/js/emoji.js#L76', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 26, 13, 32, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 676610721, 'comment_body': "One thing, I updated is added the extra parameters straight to the `user_status_emoji_info`, so we don't have to call `emoji.get_emoji_details_by_name` multiple times. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 26, 13, 37, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 676619710, 'comment_body': 'Shouldn't these properties be indented at same indentation as the `$ref`? Probably something like:
```
allOf:
  - $ref: "#/components/schemas/EmojiBase"
  - properties:
      user_id:
  ```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 26, 13, 47, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 676644286, 'comment_body': '@MSurfer20, Updated!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 26, 14, 14, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677878275, 'comment_body': 'These import restrictions are there for a reason: The `static/shared` directory is shared with the mobile codebase.

We should remove the `page_params` import by handling the `text` emojiset in the caller, I think. This new function is cleaner returning all the details we have about the emoji, not a modified set depending on the currently configuration.

For blueslip, I think we can potentially change that to a `throw new Error`; ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 27, 23, 59, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677878630, 'comment_body': "I'd make the parameter required (i.e. do `throw new error` if not provided); when we migrate this file to TypeScript, we'll certainly want to make it a type error to not pass a string here.

", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 0, 0, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677881969, 'comment_body': "These are not needed; they're already present on `AbstractReaction`.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 0, 10, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677892453, 'comment_body': 'This should be calling `check_emoji_request` to validate that the emoji requested is valid.  I can add that while integrating this.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 0, 42, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677897644, 'comment_body': "These needed a more detailed description, and a `Changes` note to indicate they're new in a new feature level.

I'm taking care of that and merging this first commit.

That said, I notice as part of this that we don't have documentation for the `/users/me/status` API endpoint, which is actually pretty important; @MSurfer20 are you up for doing that one next?  Note it'll need a `Changes` entry for feature level 86, as documented in the API changelog, and probably another for when it was introduced.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 0, 59, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677899398, 'comment_body': "It seems weird for `emojiset` to be in this object, since it's a property of the current user's configuration, not the target user's.  Could we get that property later in the pipeline?  ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 1, 5, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677966287, 'comment_body': "@timabbott Coincidentally i had opened https://github.com/zulip/zulip/pull/19403 yesterday only for adding that piece of documentation, although I'd have to add the changelog info there which i had missed earlier.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 4, 37, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 678230400, 'comment_body': "I checked and found we weren't using `emojiset` anywhere, so I removed it! ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 11, 55, 14, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 678434850, 'comment_body': 'Awesome!  Posted a few quick comments on that PR.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 15, 50, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 678435890, 'comment_body': "Why do we need this `emoji_alt_code` check?  The previous `reactions.js` code did not have that behavior.

The goal for a refactor like this should be to not change the existing logic for reactions, and it seems like it could be a bug to do so here.  It's only the new `user_status` logic that might want special handling for that emojiset, I think.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 15, 51, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 678465799, 'comment_body': 'It seems like this could be written more simply using destructuring, or we could even just pass the `event`.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 16, 27, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Status emoji follow up.
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
- [x] Fix the emoji alignment issue in the set user status modal.
- [x] Allow keyboard navigation in emoji picker of set user status modal.
- [x] Fix the custom emoji not showing up.
- [x] Fix status text not updating until clicking when compose box is opened to self.


**Testing plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->
Tested localy.

**GIFs or screenshots:** <!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->

Before | After
--- | ---
![before_house_emoji](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/63820270/128127430-20b2244f-85e8-4431-9183-28f9c9f2b7b1.png) | ![after_house_emoji](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/63820270/128127435-48db7462-7f5e-4974-ba00-ccfbc3d15243.png)
![before_hurt_emoji](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/63820270/128127547-f91e7046-3009-4919-bc3f-e0c41d183bf3.png) | ![after_hurt_emoji](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/63820270/128127541-f05f72de-e2f4-423a-a881-ca1328b4976c.png)

pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 681238719, 'comment_body': 'I think this may be clearer done a few blocks up: Just below the "button role" block.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 2, 20, 7, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 681239202, 'comment_body': "// The logic below is intended for the main view; if we're in a modal, let the browser handle the key.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 2, 20, 8, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 681240252, 'comment_body': "I think we need to do this from the `server_events_dispatch.js`  code path; this logic will only help if you're composing message to yourself.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 2, 20, 10, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 682161294, 'comment_body': 'We should do something off user ID, not email. Also, we need to update the status of other users too!  Easy to test with multiple browsers.

I think cleanest would be to just check if `event.user_id` is in `compose_pm_pill.get_user_ids`, and if so, call the redraw function.  (Possibly with an added check for if `compose_pm_pill` has valid data; not sure).', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 3, 23, 13, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 682297809, 'comment_body': "Which `redraw` function? I searched but couldn't found any relevant redraw function. Did you meant `compose_actions.update_placeholder_text` only?

I checked, `compose_pm_pill` always has valid data i.e If you open the compose box with some PM recipients and close it, `compose_pm_pill.get_user_ids` will return an empty array. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 4, 5, 27, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 682315863, 'comment_body': "Yeah that's what I meant. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 4, 6, 12, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}]

Fixes #19521

**Testing plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->
Tested localy.

  -->

pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 691955143, 'comment_body': '`emoji_filename_without_extension` might be a better variable name here.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 19, 9, 42, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 691955685, 'comment_body': 'What's the thinking on the choice of `""` vs. `None` (or omitting the field) for non-animated images?  Might be a good api design thread.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 19, 9, 43, 34, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 691955995, 'comment_body': 'Needs a feature level bump and mention.  ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 19, 9, 43, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 691956277, 'comment_body': 'This should have a couple sentences explaining the background of animated GIFs, etc.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 19, 9, 44, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 691956740, 'comment_body': 'Should we use `os.path.splitext` for the extension splitting logic?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 19, 9, 44, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 691957232, 'comment_body': 'We should make sure we assert the value of `still_url` for a non-animated image somewhere in this test file.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 19, 9, 45, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 691958572, 'comment_body': "Let's extend these example responses to contain a second emoji with a non-empty `still_url`.  ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 19, 9, 47, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 691960122, 'comment_body': 'I think these functions could be simpler if we just rendered into the template some `data-animated-url` and `data-still-url` attributes that can be used to update the display without doing a lookup.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 19, 9, 49, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 703730806, 'comment_body': 'Looks like we decided to go with omitting the field, which seems like a good choice.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 7, 18, 16, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 703731442, 'comment_body': 'This should be `im.seek(0)`, for the first frame, right?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 7, 18, 17, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 703734234, 'comment_body': "The ordering of lines is odd here.  I kinda suspect that converting to PNG is likely to trigger whatever GIF plugin bugs are involved in should_resize=False anyway, so we should probably resize unconditionally here?  Not sure.  

It's worth testing with an example image that where this is relevant and seeing what happens with the resize/no-resize cases.  (I think there's a few examples in https://github.com/zulip/zulip/issues/10351).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 7, 18, 21, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 703734559, 'comment_body': 'Rather than doing these casts, we should just `assert still_image_data is not None` in this block.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 7, 18, 22, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 703734838, 'comment_body': 'Why do we have this `still` check for returning `""` here, and not a variant in the similar other code path?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 7, 18, 22, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 703744663, 'comment_body': 'Resolved this with my push.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 7, 18, 39, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 703744858, 'comment_body': 'I changed this with my push, but we need to test to determine which is the right experience.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 7, 18, 39, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 703745011, 'comment_body': 'Changed this with my push; @Riken-Shah please confirm whether you agree this change is correct.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 7, 18, 40, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 704119681, 'comment_body': 'Yeah, this seems right!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 8, 7, 18, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 706582603, 'comment_body': "Okay, So I tried adding,

![bear.gif](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3491502/47063808-a8f6a680-d191-11e8-9b22-23d0ea6d148a.gif) (It doesn't need to be resized)

And its still image looks alright,
![Screenshot 2021-09-11 at 1 49 25 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/63820270/132941497-35d9b6a6-c8ff-4045-87a6-37ed8ba0c553.png)

![raccon](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/63820270/132941559-4de9c530-fb42-428a-a28a-a4e1b95c8dc7.gif)

Its still image looks alright,
![Screenshot 2021-09-11 at 1 52 20 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/63820270/132941584-54e34938-bffb-417e-b340-1a078d67a6de.png)




 

", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 11, 8, 23, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 706582668, 'comment_body': 'So, I guess doing resize no matter what will be alright!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 11, 8, 24, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 706583446, 'comment_body': "Yeah, it's better to `assert`!", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 9, 11, 8, 32, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 638524803, 'comment_body': 'I know we could have done anything else here, but I thought doing this will maintain consistency as we are doing the same in `settings.ts` to open the modal,
https://github.com/zulip/zulip/blob/386ddf15178ea1bec70338c37c7815b9f26cabfc/frontend_tests/puppeteer_tests/settings.ts#L32', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 25, 7, 26, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 638530552, 'comment_body': 'The reason for the flake here was missing wait call to check if the mouse events are enabled after the modal is closed. 

 - Should we introduce `common.close_modal_in_modal` and `common.open_modal_in_modal` methods to `CommonUtils` as we are doing this it many other tests too?

 - Should I also add this wait call to other tests (in `realm-linkifier.ts`) to avoid any future flake?

P.S: I have used jQuery here to maintain consistency.
https://github.com/zulip/zulip/blob/386ddf15178ea1bec70338c37c7815b9f26cabfc/frontend_tests/puppeteer_tests/settings.ts#L50


', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 25, 7, 34, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 644367995, 'comment_body': 'I think it'd be well worth adding common functions for "wait for modal close" type operations and using them consistently, yeah.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 2, 22, 47, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 644861369, 'comment_body': 'Opened https://github.com/zulip/zulip/pull/18686 for this!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 3, 14, 50, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Stream member list
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
This adds a feature that we've discussed on:
https://chat.zulip.org/#narrow/stream/138-user-community/topic/List.20of.20users.20in.20current.20stream.
we're discussing the design on:
https://chat.zulip.org/#narrow/stream/101-design/topic/stream.20member.20list

**Testing Plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->


**GIFs or Screenshots:** <!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->


<!-- Also be sure to make clear, coherent commits:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html
  -->
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 305638686, 'comment_body': "We should do this as an enum-type field, rather than a string-type field.  `demote_inactive_streams` is a good example of the right structure.

(There's a lot of disadvantages to strings, varying from consuming a lot more storage in the database, to limits on the length of names to future options, to more risk of typos creating weird behavior)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 21, 22, 22, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305638762, 'comment_body': "Do we need to do a redraw unconditionally here, or can we check whether this setting is enabled?  Redraws are really expensive in the `all` state...

(Also, do we need to check for `activity.is_initialized`?  Like, is there an actual code path where it wouldn't be?).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 21, 22, 24, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305638790, 'comment_body': "It might be cleaner to just `zrequire('activity')` for this test.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 21, 22, 25, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305638815, 'comment_body': 'What is the `memo` variable name supposed to mean?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 21, 22, 26, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305638907, 'comment_body': 'We have a serious problem with overuse of the term "filter" here making it hard to understand.  

I think probably some good names would be: `narrow_filter` if you want to interact with that object, and renaming `filter_text` to `user_filter_text`.  I would do at least that second rename as a prep commit to make the rest more readable.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 21, 22, 29, 11, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305639002, 'comment_body': "This function, in general, feels really hard to read and understand.  I think there's a few reasonable options:
* Probably best, take some of these procedures that need to be used in multiple code paths, like filtering out bots, and turn them into functions in a prep commit, so that the end result is readable.
* Use the early return pattern to have the pre-existing code look the same as before to make the diff understandable
* Just move to two functions for the two different use cases; they are completely different algorithms
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 21, 22, 31, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305639150, 'comment_body': 'Maybe this should be called `buddy_list_style`?  And then the values would be
```
BUDDY_LIST_STYLE_ALL_USERS = 1
BUDDY_LIST_STYLE_MEMBERS = 2
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 21, 22, 34, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305642203, 'comment_body': 'maybe BUDDY_LIST_STYLE_RECIPIENTS? 
When I see "all users vs members" I jump to "all users includes guests, and members doesn't". ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 21, 23, 51, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'rishig', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305647078, 'comment_body': 'I also think I should switch over `user_member_list` to `should_use_member_list`, `use_pm_with_filter` to `should_use_pm_member_list` and `use_stream_filter ` to `should_use_stream_member_list`.

This is just in addition to the renames of `filter` to `narrow_filter` and `filter_text` to `user_filter_text`.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 22, 1, 8, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'YashRE42', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305647644, 'comment_body': "That's just the typical name for the first parameter of the call back for `_.reduce`, it's what the underscore docs use but I understand that it's a bit confusing.

1. I could add a link to the docs in a comment (although that wouldn't be helpful because they don't actually give an example of constructing an array).
2. I could link to https://stackoverflow.com/a/30804674 for where I got the idea from.
3. Or I could rename `memo` to `accumulator`.

what would be the most sensible option?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 22, 1, 15, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'YashRE42', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305653356, 'comment_body': "You're right,
In fact, maybe I should maintain a duplicate list (internally) just to ensure that we actually do need a redraw...

will look into it. 
(and yeah, maybe that check on `activity.is_initialized()` is unnecessary...)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 22, 2, 8, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'YashRE42', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305653518, 'comment_body': "oh, okay, I'll change that then.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 22, 2, 10, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'YashRE42', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 305654636, 'comment_body': "is `style` really the best we could do here?
I used `content` above but why not use something like `mode`. (although that only semantically makes sense as a suffix...)

so:
```
BUDDY_LIST_ALL_USERS_MODE = 1
BUDDY_LIST_MEMBERS_MODE = 2
```

or maybe the prefix `RECIPIENT_MODE`?

I'll wait on changing the modal until we figure out the name :sweat_smile:.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2019, 7, 22, 2, 20, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'YashRE42', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 403741826, 'comment_body': "We don't really need these `if (user_filter_text)` conditions--the function `filter_user_ids` does the right thing here.

What's our policy on not-recently-active users when we're in a narrow, @timabbott?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 4, 5, 18, 49, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'showell', 'type': 'User'}]

  -->

https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/63820270/130060195-fc7b5be0-e40e-4914-b260-80f37d34567f.mov

  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html

pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 685207321, 'comment_body': "Hmm, I think we could instead address this issue by having `activity.redraw()` be a noop if the `activity` module hasn't been initialized yet, which is easy to keep track of with a global variable within that module.

(Since fundamentally it'll get drawn properly afterwards).

That said, can you explain the call path through which initializing the hashchange module ends up calling `activity.redraw`?  I'm not sure I understand why that would happen.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 9, 13, 46, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686597740, 'comment_body': "Yeah my bad,  I didn't confirm the changes in this commit. 

Actually the reason, we are initialising `hashchange` after `activity` is because when the hash is `/`, `/#` or `#recent_topics`, it calls [`recent_topics_ui.show()`](https://github.com/zulip/zulip/blob/1bdb7b1141e575f7cd4c0b259363b2979a2da4f2/static/js/recent_topics_ui.js#L577) and cause [`recent_topics_util.is_in_focus()`](https://github.com/zulip/zulip/blob/1bdb7b1141e575f7cd4c0b259363b2979a2da4f2/static/js/recent_topics_util.js#L11) to become `true`, which will lead this [code to execute](https://github.com/zulip/zulip/pull/19541/commits/40a6017229607b6d2ebfcc9d6950730ac7026a8d#diff-0610f2177e740845f3941acfaefa8097f2c86eac9c4f7bcaacbe0a91e650ccadR515-R517) and eventually cause error in 

https://github.com/zulip/zulip/blob/1bdb7b1141e575f7cd4c0b259363b2979a2da4f2/static/js/recent_topics_ui.js#L153-L156


I have fixed this by adding a check in `recent_topics_util.is_in_focus()` to confirm at least one row is there.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 8, 6, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: custom_check: Avoid use of `assert` to avoid confusion with `assert.equal`.
pr_body:
This PR bans the use of `assert` and replaces it
with `assert.ok` to avoid confusion with `assert.equal`.

Fixes #18687.

This replaces every `assert` with `assert.ok` except,
```bash
frontend_tests/puppeteer_tests/settings.ts
177:    assert(common.get_text_from_selector(page, name_field_selector), "Bot 1");
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
201:    assert(common.get_text_from_selector(page, name_field_selector), "Bot one");
```
As this would be removed in https://github.com/zulip/zulip/pull/18744.

<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->


**Testing plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->
Tested by running node tests and puppeteer tests.


**GIFs or screenshots:** <!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->
Example of the error message,
![Screenshot 2021-06-10 at 12 36 30 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/63820270/121480549-d2227000-c9e8-11eb-90d5-f64f7b60aec8.png)


<!-- Also be sure to make clear, coherent commits:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html
  -->

There’s no reason to look for the right parenthesis, and that will fail for calls that wrap across multiple lines.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 10, 8, 13, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'andersk', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 648965186, 'comment_body': 'Done!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 10, 8, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Riken-Shah', 'type': 'User'}]

> You need to update things that call this script when renaming it.

~I changed the parse script args description to  'This ~script~ file cleans unused Zulip caches.'~
~Do I also need to change this file location to avoid having `scripts/` in its location name?~
~And anything else than this?~

Okay, You meant I need to update other occurrences of it,
```bash
riken@zulip:~/zulip$ git grep -n clean-unused-caches
.github/workflows/zulip-ci.yml:118:          # scripts/lib/clean-unused-caches --verbose --threshold 0

pr_title: puppeteer: Fix the element becoming stale.
pr_body:
As the right sidebar re-renders many times, often the
element puppeteer selected becomes stale, to avoid this
issue we are using javascript to click on the element.

This PR also ensures that the set user status modal
is completely open before we start clicking.

pr_title: puppeteer_test: Improve how we select the typeahead element.
pr_body:
Our typeahead system is very sensitive, a simple internal
focus can hide it. This leads to occasional failure on the
puppeteer test.

This commit tries to solve it by clicking via javascript
instead of manual puppeteer click.

<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->


**Testing plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->


**GIFs or screenshots:** <!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->


<!-- Also be sure to make clear, coherent commits:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html
  -->

[{'comment_id': 673329386, 'comment_body': 'With the typeahead fix, does the normal `await entry!.click()` work?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 20, 17, 23, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'andersk', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 673336270, 'comment_body': "Just fix the delegation above and you won’t have to write so much spaghetti logic.

```diff
       this.$menu
-        .on('click', this.click.bind(this))
+        .on('click', 'li', this.click.bind(this))
         .on('mouseenter', 'li', this.mouseenter.bind(this))
```
